IN THE SPIRIT. We‚Äôve updated our Membership program with more levels (and benefits) for all to be able to join. 
There are a variety of ways your tax-deductible donations can aid the Foundation. ¬∑  ToFF currently has three immediate financial underwriting needs.

o  A new, more interactive Foundation website;

o  A new Data Management system to document and record our growing collection;

o  Additional on-site storage capability to house art donations. ¬∑  The Foundation offers 10 different membership levels starting at $25 for artists, $40 for TOM‚Äôs Crew members, up to $5,000 for TOM‚Äôs Lifetime Benefactors. ¬∑  Remembering the Foundation when preparing your estate planning. The Foundation welcomes, and continues to accept erotic art and other gifts from donors. 
Members are the best ambassadors the Foundation can have and we count on them to help us spread the word about ToFF‚Äôs purpose. Please, if you are not already, become a member and share your commitment and support for ToFF with others. 
We look forward to hearing from you. Please see link in our bio to TOM‚Äôs Blog on in our stories.

Independence Day | 6th December 
From the late 12th century until 1809, Finland was part of Sweden, a legacy reflected in the prevalence of the Swedish language and its official status. It then became the Grand Duchy of Finland, an autonomous duchy within the Russian Empire, until the Russian Revolution which prompted the Finnish Declaration of Independence in 1917.

In 1906, Finland became the first nation in the world to give full suffrage (the right to vote and to run for office) to all adult citizens, including women.

This Nordic country is a top performer in numerous metrics of national performance, including education, economic competitiveness, civil liberties, quality of life, and human development. 
And yes, text messaging was invented by a Finn!

"This @benyoudanart exhibition is a sex positive, unashamedly celebratory show. Eroticism doesn‚Äôt need censorship, is it something to be championed." ‚ÄúThe work is an exuberant celebration of male beauty, the male form and its erotic nature. The archetype of the Leatherman is obviously high in profile at TOM House but it‚Äôs one that often finds itself being derided or mocked in both popular culture and, sadly too often, the gay community itself. Preconceptions of masculinity harm both our sense of our own identity, our sexuality and our freedom to express ourselves.‚Äù Reception 6-9p
